Most sister ESUs were found in allopatry indicating the importance of
geographical isolation in the diversification of sea cucumbers. Allopatric
speciation appears to be the most common mode in animals \cite{Coyne2004} and is
also the most prevalent mode in marine organisms (e.g.,
\cite{Meyer2005-evolution, Malay2010}).

We detected a consistent pattern of isolation-by-distance for the three orders
we sampled more thoroughly despite differences in dispersal potential. Our
results suggest that on average, ESUs with large geographical ranges show higher
levels of genetic differentiation, but some species share a common haplotype
across the Indo-Pacific. The type of larva does not seem to affect the amount of
genetic differentiation expected across the range as evidenced by the common
slope and intercept estimated across orders. However, the Dendrochirotida with
their lecithotrophic larvae, have smaller range sizes than the orders with
planktotrophic larvae. Both Apodida and Aspidochirotida have ESUs that span the
entire Indo-Pacific while only a few Dendrochirotida have ESUs that span either
the Indian or the Pacific oceans. These results suggest that the type of larvae
influence patterns of diversity and modes of diversification.

As species of Apodida and Aspidochirotida can maintain connectivity across very
large distances, opportunities for gene flow interruptions are limited in the
present geographical context of the Indo-Pacific. The geographical location of
the barriers between allopatric sister ESUs for the Holothuriidae indicate that
separation between the Indian and Pacific Oceans, the Red Sea and the Hawaiian
archipelago are the three main barriers to cladogenesis (Fig.~
\ref{fig:map-barriers}). The Indian Ocean and the Pacific Ocean were isolated
several times throughout the Pleistocene \cite{Voris2000} which could have
contributed to the isolation and divergence of the species across the
Indo-Pacific Barrier (IBP). The IBP is a recognized marine biogeographic
barrier, and in a recent review, 15 out of 18 species of fish and invertebrates
surveyed showed genetic differentiation across this barrier
\cite{Gaither2010}. Here we found, xx\% of the species to show differences...

Typically, Dendrochirotida species have restricted ranges, with many species
known from a single locality, and species within a genus often strictly
allopatric. In the Indo-Pacific, most species of Dendrochirotida are restricted
to continental areas, with \textit{Afrocucumis africana} being the only species
that reach the Central Pacific. This pattern could be explained by the
combination of limited dispersal abilities that make the insular Pacific
difficult to reach, and the suspension feeding mode of this group that cannot
inhabit the oligotrophic environments that constitute oceanic islands
\cite{Michonneau2013}. The limited dispersal abilities of the Dendrochirotida
also lead to a different mode of diversification where speciation can occur at
small spatial scales, including along continental margins, a pattern that is not
observed in Aspidochirotida or the Apodida.

Compared to other studies on marine organisms, we recovered a higher proportion
of sister ESUs occurring in sympatry for the Holothuriidae. For instance, all
ESUs are strictly allopatric in \cite{Meyer2005-evolution}, and one out of 40
ESUs are sympatric in \cite{Malay2010}. This difference could be the result of
sympatric speciation, higher rates of secondary sympatry (speciation occurred in
allopatry, but the resulting species extended their ranges, and are now
sympatric), or a sampling artifact (the actual sister species has not been
sampled). Two lines of evidence lend support for the hypothesis of range
expansion. First, the high dispersal abilities of the Aspidochirotida make the
colonization of distant habitats possible once the barrier to dispersal has been
removed. For instance, the Red Sea experienced several salinity crises, the
latest as early as \textit{ca.} 19,000 years ago
\cite{DiBattista2013}. Therefore, the Red Sea fauna must have colonized the area
from outside refugia following the salinity crisis. Of the 30 ESUs occurring in
the Red Sea, five occur throughout the Indo-Pacific suggesting that they
expended their ranges recently and rapidly.

Second, many closely related ESUs occur in sympatry, indicating that
reproductive isolation can be completed rapidly. For instance, in Chapter~2, we
showed how 3 ESUs in the \textit{Holothuria impatiens} complex, occur in
sympatry even though they diverged less than 2 millions years ago. Four out of
the eight complexes with three or more ESUs, have ESUs with overlapping
ranges. This contrasts with other marine organisms, for which secondary sympatry
in oceanic settings occurs slowly and takes at minimum 2 millions years but
often more than 10 millions years \cite{Meyer2005-evolution, Quenouille2011,
  Malay2010, Hodge2012}. The rapid acquisition of reproductive isolation could
arise from premating isolation barriers such as differences in the timing of
gamete release or gametic incompatibilities caused by the gamete recognition
proteins (GRPs). GRPs are known to evolve rapidly and play a critical role in
fecundation success of many free spawning marine invertebrates such as sea
urchins \cite{Levitan2006, Lessios2011} and gastropods \cite{Hellberg2000}. For
instance, strong positive selection has been detected in the GRPs between
closely related species of sea urchins in sympatry but not in allopatry
\cite{Geyer2003}, suggesting the role of these proteins in maintaining species
limits.  GRPs have not yet been identified in sea cucumbers but bindin is known
from sea urchins \cite{Lessios2011} and sea stars \cite{Patino2009} which
indicates that it is plesiomorphic in the clade that sea cucumbers emerged from.

